Tetsuya Theodore Fujita is an American professor of geophysical
science.  He is one of the world's foremost authorities on violent
storms.  He discovered that most tornadoes are actually six or seven
small twisters called suction vortices, rotating around the center of
a larger tornado.  He developed a 1 to 5 scale for measuring the
strength of tornadoes.  However, his best work may be on other air
movements called downbursts and microbursts.  It is believed these
phenomena have been the cause of 17 aircraft accidents in the past 15
years.  His work helped persuade the FAA to install new radars at
major airports.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d11"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900619-0006"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="B">
  
1990 is fast becoming one of the worst years on record for tornadoes
and flooding across the middle and southern sections of the country.
One tornado in Kansas was the strongest since 1985.  Flooding in the
South and the Plains has been as destructive as the tornadoes.
Studies of tornadoes indicate they are concentrated in regions for
five or six year periods.  Parts of the Midwest, particularly Kansas
and Missouri, seem to be entering such a trend.  However, because
computers allow meteorologists to see more sources of data more
clearly, warning of impending storms is becoming more sophisticated
leading to fewer deaths.</SUM>
